To calculate the difference in the number of words Cam can type before and after breaking his arm over a period of five minutes, we start by determining how many words he was able to type with each hand.

Before the injury, Cam could type at a rate of 9 words per minute. Over 5 minutes, this would mean:

\[ \text{Words typed in 5 minutes before} = 9 \, \text{words/minute} \times 5 \, \text{minutes} = 45 \, \text{words} \]

After breaking his arm and having to use his left hand temporarily, Cam's typing speed decreased to 6 words per minute. Over the same 5-minute period:

\[ \text{Words typed in 5 minutes after injury} = 6 \, \text{words/minute} \times 5 \, \text{minutes} = 30 \, \text{words} \]

To find the difference in the number of words Cam could type before and after breaking his arm over this period:

\[ \text{Difference} = 45 \, \text{words} - 30 \, \text{words} = 15 \, \text{words} \]

Therefore, Cam would have typed 15 more words with his right hand than with his left hand in a span of five minutes. The answer is:

\[ \boxed{15} \]
